    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-06-01T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-06-01T12:00:00-05:00" n="311"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d311">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">724.3415/3781: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-06-01T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >June 1, 1934—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 1—2:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>123. Department’s 49, May 31, 8 p.m., first paragraph. General reaction here to
                    the United States position in the matter of the Chaco arms embargo is one of
                    extreme gratification. Current reports of the favorable steps being taken by
                    Congress even prior to the formal declaration of the embargo obviously
                    stimulated action by other states. League officials also from a technical point
                    of view regard the declaration as evidence that in specific cases judged by the
                    United States on their merits the latter is willing to cooperate effectively
                    with the peace machinery of the League. Expressions of satisfaction have been
                    made <pb facs="0321" n="251" xml:id="pg_251"/> to me by officials of a large
                    number of delegations even in quarters where it might be suspected that the
                    prompt action of the United States was received with some dismay as eliminating
                    an excuse for delay or for the adoption of a negative attitude.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
